## Environments

Environments are a whitelist declared in `penv.config.ts`. They are **not** inferred from folders or filenames — a filename segment counts as an environment only if it appears in the whitelist. This is what keeps environment scoping and namespace folders from ever being ambiguous.

```ts
// penv.config.ts
export default {
  environments: ["local", "development", "staging", "production"],
};
```

### Resolution order

For a target environment, penv resolves each parameter as:

1. `<name>.local` — your personal gitignored override (highest precedence)
2. `<name>.<env>` — the shared environment value
3. `<name>` — the unscoped default (fallback)

**Fallback is never silent.** Any parameter resolving via the unscoped default for a real environment is reported by `penv doctor`, so a production value quietly coming from a shared default cannot hide. Ask penv which file wins at any time:

```bash
penv get database-url --env production --explain
# → resolves to .penv/database-url.production.enc
```

