## `penv doctor`

The fastest way to see penv's value without restructuring anything. Point it at your local config and a live provider; it produces one report of everything that has drifted.

```
$ penv doctor

✓ Schema valid
⚠ Missing parameter         redis.password      required for production, absent
⚠ Weak secret               app.jwt-secret      18 chars, schema requires ≥32
⚠ Unused parameter          LEGACY_API_KEY      present, not in schema
⚠ Drifted from provider     stripe.secret-key   local ≠ vault:secret/production
⚠ Unscoped fallback in use  api-url             production resolving to default
⚠ Plaintext secret          db-password.staging value file is not encrypted
✓ Encryption enabled
✓ Provider                  vault
```

Every warning names the parameter and the concrete problem. The filesystem model becomes the natural next step for teams who want to *fix* what doctor surfaces — it is not required to get value from the report.

> `penv doctor`'s cross-provider drift check needs to know how your local names map to provider paths. That correspondence comes from `penv.config.ts`. Getting a useful report is fast, but it is not literally zero-config — the mapping is the small amount you supply.

